@NODE "Usage" "Typical Z80Simulator usage scenario:"
@{FG SHINE}
  A typical development cycle might go as follows: @{FG TEXT}
  
  1. You've written your Z80 source code for the target hardware.

  2. (Optional) Run Z80Simulator & select the @{" Macro " LINK "Macro"} menu 
     item or run @{B}Macro <srcfile >outputfile@{UB} outside of
     the Z80Simulator program & verify that your code was pre-processed
     without errors.
     
  3. Run Z80Simulator & select the @{" Assemble " LINK "Assemble"} menu item
     or run @{B}Z80Asm srcfile -l listfile -o objectfile@{UB} outside of
     the Z80Simulator program & verify that your code assembled without
     errors.

  4. Select the @{" Translate " LINK "Translate"} menuitem or run 
     @{B}Z80Xlate <objectfile >output.cfg@{UB} outside of the Z80Simulator
     program & verify that your code is translated properly.

  5. Select the @{" Load " LINK "Load"} menu item & select your new
     configuration file.
  
  6. You might want to @{" set some break points " LINK "SetBrkPt"} before the next step.
  
  7. Once your configuration file is loaded, select the @{" Restart " LINK "Restart"} or
     @{" Go " LINK "Go"} menu item in order to start your code in the
     Simulation.  NOTE:  @{B}Go@{UB} will run until your code executes a @{B}HALT@{UB}
     instruction (0x76).
  
  8. If you use the @{B}Restart@{UB} menu item, the Simulation will start at address
     0000 (just like a real Z80 would).  You can then use the @{" Step " LINK "Step"}
     menu item (use the A-T key combination) to single-step through your
     Z80 source code & verify that it does what you designed it to do.
     
  9. If you find a problem in step 8, return to step 1 & repeat this
     process.
@ENDNODE

