@NODE "configformat" "Z80Simulator Configuration file format:" 
   A configuration file is broken up into different segments by the
  @{BOLD "\@"}symbol.
    
   First, all initial register values are specified via the@{SHINE REG}command.

  @{SHINE LOAD}specifies a starting address, followed by the bytes to load into
   the Z80 memory space, which is how your Z80 program gets loaded.
   
  @{SHINE BREAK}specifies a break point to add to the simulation environ-
   ment.  The following values are used to indicate the register the
   breakpoint is for:
   @{FG SHINE}   
   A  - 0      E  - 8      I   - 16     IX - 24
   AP - 1      EP - 9      R   - 17     IY - 25
   B  - 2      H  - 10     BC  - 18     SP - 26
   BP - 3      HP - 11     BCP - 19     PC - 27
   C  - 4      L  - 12     DE  - 20
   CP - 5      LP - 13     DEP - 21
   D  - 6      F  - 14     HL  - 22
   DP - 7      FP - 15     HLP - 23
   @{FG TEXT}
   (Example:  AP is the alternate A-register, H is the H-register).

   After the register designator, there is one or two bytes (for 16-bit
   registers), which indicate the value the register is going to break at.
   
   The@{SHINE END}command tells@{BOLD Z80Simulator}that the end of the configuration
   file has been reached.

   See Also, @{" Z80.cfg " LINK "z80.cfg/main"} - default configuration file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Z80Asm" "Z80 Assembler:"

   Z80Asm is a Z80 Assembler written by William C. Colley (C) 1986-1988.
   I Obtained it from the C Users Journal (CUG #276).  This assembler
   does not have Macro capability, which is why I wrote my own @{" Macro " LINK "MacroCmd"}
   program.

   (see @{" Assembler manual " LINK "Z80Assembler.doc/main"})   
    
   See Also, @{" Macro program description " LINK "MacroCmd"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "MacroCmd" "Z80Simulator Macro program:"

   I wrote this Macro program because the @{" Z80 Assembler " LINK "Z80Asm"} did NOT have Macro
   capabilities.

   To use a macro in your source code, simply place the macro name (& any
   arguments, up to ten) where you want the macro to be expanded.  Example:
   
   ...
   LD BC,1122H @{FG SHINE}
   \@Reset_Acc @{FG TEXT}  ; The macro to include.
   JP  Wherever
   ...
   
   @{B}\@Reset_Acc@{UB} will be expanded to:

   ...
   LD BC,1122H @{FG SHINE}
;Macro Reset_Acc
   XOR A @{FG TEXT}
   JP  Wherever
   ...
   
   See Also, @{" Example macro definitions " LINK "Z80.macros/main"}

@ENDNODE

