@NODE "Load" "Z80Simulator Load configuration Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open an ASL file requester for you to find & select
   a Z80Simulator @{" configuration " LINK "configformat"} file.  No
   indication will be given if the operation is successful.
      
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Save" "Z80Simulator Save configuration Menu Item:"
@NEXT "SaveAs"
@PREV "Load"
   This menu item will open an ASL file requester (if necessary) for you to
   find & select a Z80Simulator @{" configuration " LINK "configformat"} file name to 
   use.  No indication will be given if the operation is successful.
   
   See Also @{" Save As menu item " LINK "SaveAs"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SaveAs" "Z80Simulator SaveAs configuration Menu Item:"

@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Save"
   This menu item will open an ASL file requester for you to find & select
   a Z80Simulator @{" configuration " LINK "configformat"} file name to 
   use.  No indication will be given if the operation is successful.
   
   See Also @{" Save menu item " LINK "Save"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "About" "Z80Simulator About Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open an @{" Information Requester " LINK "AboutReq"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Quit" "Z80Simulator Quit Menu Item:"

   This menu item will first verify your sanity before exiting the Program.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Translate" "Z80Simulator Translate Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open a requester so that you can enter information
   the program needs to translate an Intel-format object file into
   a configuration file that the Z80Simulator understands.

   @{B}Z80Asm@{UB} will generate its output in Intel-format.
      
   See Also, @{" Translate Requester " LINK "TranslateReq"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Edit" "Z80Simulator Edit Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open an ASL file requester for you to find & select
   a file name to edit.  The program will then use the editor you specified
   in the @{" Icon ToolTypes " LINK "ToolTypes"} to edit the file. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Macro" "Z80Simulator Macro Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open a @{" command requester " LINK "CmdReq"} for you to enter in 
   parameters the @{B}Macro@{UB} program will use to pre-process your Z80 source 
   code.  This allows you to use a different Macro program than the one
   provided by @{" myself " LINK "Author"}.

   See Also, @{" Icon ToolTypes " LINK "ToolTypes"}, @{" Macro program description " LINK "MacroCmd"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Assemble" "Z80Simulator Assemble Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open a @{" command requester " LINK "CmdReq"} for you to enter in 
   parameters the @{B}Z80Asm@{UB} program will use to assemble your Z80 
   source code.  This allows you to use a different Assembler program than 
   the one provided by @{" myself " LINK "Author"}.

   See Also, @{" Icon ToolTypes " LINK "ToolTypes"}, @{" Assembler manual " LINK "Z80Assembler.doc/main"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "PrtListing" "Z80Simulator Print Listing Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open a @{" Print Listing " LINK "PrtListingReq"} requester
   so that you can specify how much of your source code should be 
   re-assembled back into source code & sent to the printer.
    
@ENDNODE

@NODE "FindCurrent" "Z80Simulator Find Current Instruction Menu Item:"

   This menu item simply highlights the Z80 instruction that the program
   will execute next, if the @{" Step " LINK "Step"} menu item is selected (for example).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SetRegisterVal" "Z80Simulator Set Register Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open a @{" Set Register " LINK "SetRegisterReq"} requester
   so that you can specify any (or all) Z80 registers that should be 
   preset to a given value.  The program will then use that value in the
   rest of the simulation.  Any changes you make are @{B}NOT@{UB} kept by the
   program.  It's up to you to keep track of your own Z80 source code
   changes!
   
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Dump" "Z80Simulator Dump Memory Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open a @{" Dump Memory " LINK "DumpMemoryReq"} requester
   so that you can specify what part of the Z80 memory space you wish
   to view in another window.
   
   See Also, @{" Dump Stack Menu Item " LINK "Stack"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Fill" "Z80Simulator Fill Memory Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open a @{" Fill Memory " LINK "FillMemoryReq"} requester
   so that you can specify what part of the Z80 memory space you wish
   to fill & the data to fill with.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Stack" "Z80Simulator Dump Stack Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open a @{" Dump Stack " LINK "DumpStackReq"} requester
   so that you can specify what part of the Z80 stack space you wish
   to view in another window.
   
   See Also, @{" Dump Memory Menu Item " LINK "Dump"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Step" "Z80Simulator Step Menu Item:"

   This menu item is used to execute a single instruction of your source
   code & show you how it affects the internal Z80 registers.  @{" Other " LINK "Dump"} menu
   items allow you to examine memory locations.
   
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Restart" "Z80Simulator Restart Menu Item:"

   This menu item will set the Z80 program counter to 0000, as if your 
   hardware has asserted a *RESET* on the Z80 processor.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "NMI" "Z80Simulator *NMI* Menu Item:"

   This menu item will set the Z80 program counter to address 0066H, as if
   your hardware has asserted a *NMI* on the Z80 processor. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE "INT" "Z80Simulator *INT* Menu Item:"

   This menu item will act as if your hardware has asserted a *INT* on the 
   Z80 processor.  Depending on the state of the @{B}IFF1 & IFF2@{UB} bits inside
   the simulation, the program will perform the appropriate type of
   Interrupt that the bits indicate (including none at all if the @{B}DI@{UB} opcode
   has been executed & you haven't executed an @{B}EI@{UB} opcode yet).  

   See Also, @{" Interrupt Mode 0 " LINK "IM0Req"}, @{" Interrupt Mode 2 " LINK "IM2Req"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Go" "Z80Simulator Go! Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open a @{" Start Address " LINK "StartAddrReq"} requester
   so that you can specify the starting address for the simulation.  The 
   Z80Simulator will continue to execute your Z80 code until either a 
   @{B}HALT@{UB} instruction is executed or an ILLEGAL opcode is found.
   There is no other way yo interrupt this, so set some break points if
   you expect a long stretch of Z80 code to get executed before a HALT
   opcode will be found.  Z80Simulator will fill the simulation memory
   space with @{B}HALT@{UB} opcodes before your configuration file is loaded, so as
   long as you don't use all of the Z80 memory space for your code, you're
   guaranteed to execute a @{B}HALT@{UB} at some point.
   
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SetPC" "Z80Simulator Set PC Menu Item:"

   This menu item will open a @{" Start Address " LINK "StartAddrReq"} requester
   so that you can specify the address to place in the Z80 program counter.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "SetBrkPt" "Z80Simulator Set Break Point Menu Item:"
   
   This menu item will open a @{" Set Break Point " LINK "SetBrkPtReq"} requester
   so that you can set a register value to discontinue executing your 
   source code at.  This can be any register (except for the IFF0 & IFF1
   bits).
   
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ClrBrkPt" "Z80Simulator Clear Break Point Menu Item:"
   
   This menu item will open a @{" Clear Break Point " LINK "ClrBrkPtReq"} requester
   so that you can remove a break point from the simulation.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ShowBrkPt" "Z80Simulator Show Break Point Menu Item:"
   
   This menu item will open a @{" Show Break Point " LINK "ShowBrkPtReq"} requester 
   so that you can see the break points the Z80Simulator knows about.
@ENDNODE
